<font color="#FF0000">HISTORICAL LIES FOR LIARS</font><br>
<tt>Mon Nov  3 20:27:54 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
MTF has made a valid point.  We will continue to re-write history until it matches the expectations of the politicians that created it.  We are the pawns in this great game of global chess.  We fit neatly into the sanitary area of acceptable losses.  Acceptable losses, something the politicians never want to talk about openly.<br><br>
Look at the history of the Native Americans.  I stress Americans, a name that the US wanted to deny the American Indian.  Even now they want to use polite names instead of proud names and heritage.  We have tried to strip away their identity.  Buried them in reservations and refused to give them a voice in history.  In every war they are given the equal opportunity to die.  My dad fought beside a man called White Bear of the Minnesota Sioux (he had no other name) during WWII.  As he said, a hell of a guy.  There is no public outcry to right the wrong.  Why?<br><br>
I have studied the Indian wars.  Wrote a paper for the University of Nebraska and Fort Crook museum in the late 1970s.  I did not know about history of the native Americans until that time.  I found the biggest bunch of lies ever published.  An attempt to sweep everything under the rug.  The University of Arizona helped me with the real facts and diaries of real people.<br><br>
Ed was correct.  Custer was a politically hungry inept idiot in every aspect.  He thought of the Indian as cannon fodder for his ambitions.  He was ordered to not go to the Big Horn.  All real soldiers knew better.  Had he lived, General Crook would have probably court marshaled him.  The press swung the tide of public opinion to meet the political needs.  Crook said the one thing the Indian could not learn from the White man was how to lie.  Their word was their bond and they expected the same from us.  We used it against them.  The white politician knew how to lie.  An attempted genocide was planned with women, children, elderly, and sometimes warriors as the targets from the Pacific Northwest to the Eastern U.S..  Sound familiar.  The Pacific Northwest and the Great Plains was the primary focus.  They had land we wanted.  We made deals and continued to break them.  We starved them by not supplying food knowing they would leave the reservation to feed themselves.  We then persecuted them for not starving without a struggle.  General Crook spoke out in disgust and was promptly taken to Chicago and forced to retire by a man our history holds in high esteem.  Custer the Dog is better known than Crook.  Politically correct.<br><br>
I could go on because this is really one of my sore spots.  We have become humanitarian hypocrites.  Our methods don't change just our targets.  The Native American honored family, tribe, and his pony above all else.  He did not understand about owning land.  Man could not own the land.  It belonged to a higher force that allowed us to be a part of it.  What is the greater good?  Watch a politician dance with that explanation.  Usually what you have, why I want it, and how I plan on taking it away from you, and who I will get to do my dirty work.<br><br>
As MTF has said, Who is going to do anything about it?  If we have learned anything at all we should know that if you can't be heard you will change nothing.  Problems without solutions fall on deaf ears.<br><br>
Enough!  Ed, Why the hell didn't you know this was one of my trigger points.<br>

<p><code>-- Injustice at its worst  (SW) </code><p>


